n primary" href=3D"https://www.robkhenderson.com/subscribe?&amp;gift=3Dtrue=
" rel=3D""><span>Give a gift subscription</span></a></p><p><span>Despite fa=
mily-friendly social and economic policies, birthrates are falling in many =
rich countries. A </span><a href=3D"https://www.ft.com/content/500c0fb7-a04=
a-4f87-9b93-bf65045b9401?fbclid=3DIwAR2OJv55ZImYEHDjvv56p10cThMHvK_6Ste84nA=
gtkg5K3S9rt-CAS8JSPc" rel=3D"">recent article</a><span> in the </span><em>F=
inancial Times</em><span> notes that past declines were driven by families =
having fewer children, but now people are skipping having children altogeth=
er. =E2=80=9CNobody really knows what=E2=80=99s going on,=E2=80=9D writes <=
/span><em>FT</em><span>. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s not primarily driven by econ=
omics or family policies. It=E2=80=99s something cultural, psychological.=
=E2=80=9D</span></p><p><span>An </span><em>Economist </em><a href=3D"https:=
//www.economist.com/leaders/2024/05/23/why-paying-women-to-have-more-babies=
-wont-work" rel=3D"">analysis</a><span> published last year offers an answe=
r to the mystery. Many assume that declining birthrates owe mainly to colle=
ge-educated women delaying motherhood=E2=80=94putting off having kids for t=
oo long and ultimately having fewer children than they wanted. This belief =
has shaped policy responses, emphasizing tax breaks and subsidized childcar=
e to help women balance careers and family life. But according to </span><e=
m>The Economist</em><span>, that=E2=80=99s not what=E2=80=99s happening.</s=
pan></p><p>Though college-educated women are having children later, the shi=
ft is minor. In the U.S., the average age of first-time motherhood for this=
 group has risen only slightly, from 28 in 2000 to 30 today. These women st=
ill have about as many kids as their peers did a generation ago=E2=80=94jus=
t slightly fewer than what they say would be ideal, which has always been t=
he case.</p><p>The real drivers of falling fertility rates in wealthy count=
ries, it turns out, aren=E2=80=99t professional women but younger, poorer w=
omen, who are delaying childbirth and ultimately having fewer children. In =
the U.S., more than half of the fertility drop since 1990 comes from a shar=
p decline in births among teenagers, partly because more of them are attend=
ing college. Even among those not going to college, birthrates are down. In=
 1994, the average first-time mother without a college degree was 20. Today=
, about two-thirds of women without degrees in their twenties still haven=
=E2=80=99t had a first child.</p><p><span>A generation ago, poorer women of=
ten had children with the hope that doing so would lead to marriage and fam=
ily stability. This bet rarely worked out. In </span><em><a href=3D"https:/=
/www.amazon.com/Promises-Can-Keep-Motherhood-Marriage/dp/0520241134" rel=3D=
"">Promises I Can Keep: Why Poor Women Put Motherhood Before Marriage</a></=
em><span> (2005), sociologists Kathryn Edin and Maria Kefalas chronicle res=
earch from the 1990s and early 2000s showing that, when these women had a b=
aby, eight out of ten were still in a relationship with the </span><a href=
=3D"https://www.robkhenderson.com/p/no-one-expects-young-men-to-do-anything=
" rel=3D"">child=E2=80=99s father</a><span>, and nearly half lived together=
. In other words, most =E2=80=9Csingle mothers=E2=80=9D weren=E2=80=99t tru=
ly single at the time of their child=E2=80=99s birth; they were unmarried b=
ut partnered. When asked about their future, nearly all these women expecte=
d to stay with their partners and eventually marry. By the baby=E2=80=99s f=
irst birthday, though, half of these couples had split. By the time the chi=
ld turned three, two-thirds had gone their separate ways.</span></p><p><spa=
n>Their Millennial and Gen Z children witnessed this failure, absorbed its =
lessons, and grew up not having kids. As I describe in my book </span><em><=
a href=3D"https://simonandschuster.com/books/Troubled/Rob-Henderson/9781982=
168537" rel=3D"">Troubled: A Memoir of Foster Care, Family, and Social Clas=
s</a></em><span>, I lived in homes during the 1990s and 2000s with two girl=
s who became mothers at 16, then had another child at 18 and another in the=
ir 20s=E2=80=94all with different fathers. Interestingly, they only had dau=
ghters. Those girls are now in their mid-twenties. None has children.</span=
></p><p><span>The kids also lack two key advantages their mothers had. Firs=
t is a mental template of a stable family. Most Baby Boomer and Gen X women=
 who had children out of wedlock had grown up in intact families and still =
believed marriage was in the cards for them. Their children, having seen th=
ose relationships fall apart, don=E2=80=99t have the same expectation. Seco=
nd, the kids lack support from married grandparents. Biological anthropolog=
ist Richard Bribiescas has </span><a href=3D"https://press.princeton.edu/bo=
oks/hardcover/9780691160634/how-men-age" rel=3D"">pointed out</a><span> tha=
t grandmothers played a crucial evolutionary role in human societies by hel=
ping care for their grandchildren, allowing their daughters to have more ch=
ildren. Even in recent decades, grandmothers could ease the childcare burde=
n because their husbands handled other responsibilities. Today, many Baby B=
oomer and Gen X women who had children outside of marriage are grandmothers=
 without partners. Without that extra support, they=E2=80=99re less able to=
 help their daughters raise kids.</span></p><p><span>Many learn about this =
decline in pregnancy among poor, unmarried women and applaud it. There=E2=
=80=99s another way to think about this, though. Fertility among married co=
uples </span><a href=3D"https://ifstudies.org/blog/no-ring-no-baby" rel=3D"=
">hasn=E2=80=99t declined</a><span>; overall birthrates have dropped largel=
y </span><a href=3D"https://ifstudies.org/blog/no-ring-no-baby" rel=3D"">be=
cause</a><span> fewer young people are getting married.</span></p><p><span>=
Thus, efforts to boost birthrates might be more effective if they focused o=
n promoting marriage. Unfortunately, as economist Melissa Kearney </span><a=
 href=3D"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3D26zD15fABjE&amp;t=3D2s" rel=3D""=
>points out</a><span> in her book </span><em>The Two-Parent Privilege</em><=
span>, cultural tastemakers are reluctant to do this. Elites can=E2=80=99t =
necessarily impose values on everyone else, but they can invalidate them. I=
n 1960, the percentage of American children living with both biological par=
ents was </span><a href=3D"https://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/books/119020/=
coming-apart-by-charles-murray" rel=3D"">identical</a><span> for affluent a=
nd working-class families=E2=80=9495 percent. By 2005, after a </span><a hr=
ef=3D"https://www.amazon.com/Dream-Nightmare-Sixties-Legacy-Underclass/dp/0=
688119514/ref=3Dsr_1_1?crid=3D1SZVZ0CVUSTHT&amp;dib=3DeyJ2IjoiMSJ9.Pi-GBXYa=
QppCTgemqxz2FgQriC-TmGsR8Tigv0KGKr10DCSgCycPnWOE8ZntDSKuXo20KV9OlpggfN_tvuR=
67xHcfozKm0zinl1cWCE2hyPDO5o40VBlt6rnrYL19BUTKoB-eUfwfTjbj_usi8HnvCPb_ojijV=
sycc0KBKgMoyBEZpuHm-NALhA1Qlvwyo7pvezG2xSjICb8U6rIIUr3rXLSUR6gJAC1v593sQcOP=
24.lzVZbU34cuqSrszReTpDlLAvnvb-9ozDENdbNOzyt0A&amp;dib_tag=3Dse&amp;keyword=
s=3Dthe+dream+and+the+nightmare&amp;qid=3D1740768950&amp;s=3Dbooks&amp;spre=
fix=3Dthe+dream+and+the+nightmar%2Cstripbooks%2C124&amp;sr=3D1-1" rel=3D"">=
decades-long elite cultural repudiation of marriage</a><span>, that figure =
remained high among affluent families (85 percent) but had plummeted to jus=
t 30 percent among working-class families.</span></p><div class=3D"captione=
d-image-container"><figure><a class=3D"image-link image2 is-viewable-img" t=
